✅ Fast Fix #4 (Best for performance): replace OUTER APPLY with one grouped join

This avoids doing a lookup per row. (Often much faster.)

SELECT TOP (5000)
    dm.GMPI_ID,
    dm.MEMBER_MBI,
    dm.MEMBER_FIRST_NAME,
    dm.MEMBER_LAST_NAME,
    dm.MEMBER_DATE_OF_BIRTH,
    CAST(ev.ER_DATE AS date) AS ER_DATE,
    ev.HOSPITAL_PROVIDER,
    ev.ER_STATUS,
    ev.ER_CATEGORY,
    ev.CLAIM_ID_ER,
    p.PROCEDURE_CODE,
    p.CODE_NAME
FROM
(
    SELECT TOP (5000) *
    FROM BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.FACT_ER_VISITS
    WHERE ER_STATUS = 'TRUE ER'
      AND ER_DATE >= DATEADD(day, -10, CAST(GETDATE() AS date))
    ORDER BY ER_DATE DESC
) ev
LEFT JOIN BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.dim_member dm
    ON dm.GMPI_ID = ev.GMPI_ID
LEFT JOIN
(
    SELECT
        fcp.CLAIM_ID,
        MAX(CASE WHEN fcp.CODE IN ('99281','99282','99283','99284','99285',
                                   'G0380','G0381','G0382','G0383','G0384')
                 THEN fcp.CODE END) AS PROCEDURE_CODE,
        MAX(CASE WHEN fcp.CODE IN ('99281','99282','99283','99284','99285',
                                   'G0380','G0381','G0382','G0383','G0384')
                 THEN fcp.CODE_NAME END) AS CODE_NAME
    FROM BI_ANALYSIS.dbo.FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE fcp
    GROUP BY fcp.CLAIM_ID
) p
    ON p.CLAIM_ID = ev.CLAIM_ID_ER
ORDER BY ev.ER_DATE DESC;

This version isn’t “perfect priority” anymore (it prioritizes ED codes only), but it is very fast for a validation run.

The real root cause (why it’s slow)

To be blunt: you probably don’t have an index on:

FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE(CLAIM_ID) or

FACT_ER_VISITS(ER_STATUS, ER_DATE)

If indexes exist, APPLY is much faster.

Quick question you can ask your DBA (sounds smart)

Can we confirm there’s an index on FACT_CLAIM_PROCEDURE(CLAIM_ID) and FACT_ER_VISITS(ER_STATUS, ER_DATE)? The OUTER APPLY is slow without it.

What I recommend you do now

Run Fast Fix #1 with TOP (50) first:

If it returns fast → logic is good.

Then increase to 500 / 5000.

If it’s still slow even at TOP 50, then indexing is likely the issue.

